I decided to complete a right join with my two datasets so that I could more easily focus on the Halloween candy statistics specifically for all 50 states, and Washington D.C without seeing all of the NA values for the Halloween candies that were not a top choice of any state. In the two separate datasets, the candy_rankings dataset had 85 observations and 14 distinct variables while the state_candy dataset had 51 observations and 3 distinct variables. However, in this right join, there were 51 observations and they were joined using 1 distinct ID variable. However, this ID variable had different names in each dataset, which had to be accounted for. Because of this, all of the original variables from the two separate datasets were present in the joined dataset, however the “Top Candy” ID variable from the state_candy dataset combined with the “competitiorname” ID variable from the candy_rankings dataset. This resulted in 16 distinct variables in the joined dataset.The state_candy dataset kept all of its observations in the joined dataset, however the candy_rankings lost 34 observations which were of candies that were no state’s favorite. Also, there were 12 candies that were in the state_candy dataset but not in the candy_rankings which led to 12 rows that contain NAs for some of the variables in the joined dataset. Lastly, there were 72 candies in the candy_rankings dataset but not in the state_candy dataset.

I was curious to know which candy had been purchased the most by weight. To figure this out, I filtered the joined_candy data so that the row with the highest Pound variable was chosen, then I selected the columns that I was interested in seeing, in this case, the columns for the candy name, the win percentage that the candy has won when it went up against other candies, the state that bought the pounds of candy, and the number of pounds that were bought. I learned that California bought the most candy, which happened to be Reese’s Peanut Butter Cups. It also worked out that this candy had the highest win percentage, which I found by arranging the data in a descending order according to win percentage.

The next numeric variable I had was winpercent, which is the percentage that the candy in question won against 269,000 matchups with other candies. First, I wanted to see just the overall average of wins throughout all the candy in the data set, which was 64.548%. Next, I wanted to see how just the chocolate group performed, and if they won more or less often than the entire group. After grouping by chocolate, the winning average for candies that contained chocolate was 66.94112% while candies without chocolate won an average of 61.45102% of the time. I also found the minimum and maximum of the candies that had chocolate and those that don’t, which shows that chocolate-containing candies might be more popular.

The last numeric variable is Pounds, which is the weight in pounds that each state bought of their favorite candy. First, I wanted to just see some characteristics about this variable. I found that the mean pounds of candy bought overall was 159,803.5 lbs with a max of 1,209,299 lbs and a min of 2873 lbs. Next, I wanted to see if the type of candy had any effect on the number of pounds bought, so I grouped by fruity type and chocolate type to see any differences. After grouping them the data showed that when fruity and chocolate type flavors are in the same candy, more pounds of the candy are sold followed by only chocolate, followed by only fruity.

Visualizing

library(ggplot2)
joined_candy %>% group_by(chocolate) %>% na.omit() %>% ggplot(aes(x = chocolate, 
    fill = chocolate)) + geom_bar(aes(y = sugarpercent), stat = "summary", 
    fun = mean) + geom_errorbar(aes(y = sugarpercent), stat = "summary", 
    fun.data = mean_se, width = 0.6) + xlab("Chocolate") + ylab("Sugar Percentile") + 
    ggtitle("Chocolate and Sugar") + theme(legend.position = "none") + 
    scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 0.8, 0.1))

This bar plot analyzes the relationship between chocolate content of a candy and how this corresponds to its sugar content. Based on this plot, it is shown that candies with chocolate seem to be in a much higher sugar percentile than all other candies without chocolate. This relationship is still seen even with the error bars on the graph, which means that on average, candies with chocolate have more sugar than those without chocolate.

joined_candy %>% ggplot(aes(x = sugarpercent, y = pricepercent)) + 
    geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "Orange") + geom_point(position = position_jitter(width = 0.1, 
    height = 0.1), color = "Purple") + scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 
    1, 0.1)) + scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 1, 0.1)) + 
    ggtitle("Price and Sugar") + xlab("Sugar Percentile") + ylab("Price Percentile")

This scatterplot itself has points which display the relationship between the sugar percentile a certain Halloween candy is in to the candy’s price percentile. This plot also has a regression line so that the relationship between these two variables can be seen more clearly. As seen in this plot, it appears that there is a positive correlation between sugar percentile and price percentile. This means that as a candy has more sugar relative to the other candies, then its price goes up relative to the other candies, on average.

joined_candy %>% ggplot(aes(x = State, fill = competitorname)) + 
    geom_bar(aes(y = Pounds), stat = "summary", fun = mean) + 
    theme(legend.position = "none", axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, 
        hjust = 1)) + scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 1e+07, 
    1e+05)) + ggtitle("Pounds of Halloween Candy") + xlab("State")

This plot clearly displays the relationship between state and the number of pounds of the state’s favorite Halloween candy that have been bought. Through this plot it is apparent that California and Texas purchased the most, while Alaska and Connecticut purchased the least. This is probably due to population differences, how much the different states celebrate Halloween, and possibly candy availability.

Concluding Remarks

Overall, this project allowed me to analyze the different consumer behaviors for Halloween candies throughout the United States, and how different types of candies can alter their popularity, amount of sugar, and their price. These relationships were able to be closely examined by using various wrangling, tidying, joining, and visualization strategies as shown throughout the project.
